{
  "text": "Although most studies have reported greater risk for depressed patients, a few have reported mixed or negative findings or small effect sizes. Ariyo et al [CITATION_1] followed 4493 patients free of cardiovascular disease at baseline for 6 years. Depression (as measured by the 10-item CES-D) was a statistically significant predictor of CHD diagnosis, but the effect size was relatively small, with a hazard ratio of 1.15 for a 5-point increase in the 10-item scale.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "20772510"
